AI/ML Team Take Home
Exercise: Predicting Chess
Game Outcomes

Overview
Using Chess.com's public API, build a model that predicts the outcome of a chess
game (win, loss, or draw for the white player), given the information available
before the game starts.
Please don’t spend more than 3-4 hours on this exercise. We respect your time
and aren’t looking for a large-scale model. We want to see how you think about an
ML problem: data collection, feature engineering, modeling, and evaluation.
Data
Your dataset comes from Titled Tuesday events, Chess.com’s weekly blitz
tournament for titled players (GMs, IMs, FMs, etc.). Each event is an 11-round
Swiss tournament with a 5-minute time control and typically 400+ participants.
We suggest using data from the following two recent events:
February 10, 2026 (455 players, 11 rounds)

http://api.chess.com/pub/tournament/titled-tuesday-blitz-february-10-2026-
6221327

March 10, 2026 (476 players, 11 rounds)

http://api.chess.com/pub/tournament/titled-tuesday-blitz-march-10-2026-
6277141

Our Published Data API (PubAPI) is public, read-only, and requires no
authentication. The tournament endpoint returns metadata about the event,
including the list of players and URLs for each round. You can traverse the round
and group endpoints to retrieve the individual games, which include player ratings,

